messages.text: OK, my vision went back to normal.
Good. Let’s focus—how are we gonna find Quentin Finch?
If I can get my hands on my dad's address book, Finch’s phone number's gotta be in there.
Dad still writes everything down on paper like it's the Middle Ages.
Are you sure we shouldn’t just tell him what's going on?
He could give us answers.
Absolutely not.
I'm already losing my freaking sanity.
I won't risk my freedom, too.
I won't let him lock me up.
Why are you so sure he'd commit you to a psych hospital?
Because he’s done it before.
What?!
Not to me…
To my mom.
Oh. You don't talk much about your mom.
Yeah, well… I haven't been dating you that long, Brooke.
Wow, OK.
I'm sorry. I don't mean to sound harsh.
I don't usually open up about my mom.
It's OK.
She had postpartum depression after I was born.
My dad took her to therapy and the psychiatrist had her committed because she was suicidal.
My aunt said the psych ward was traumatic for my mom.
Apparently she was never the same after she came home.
Then she left when I was 2.
Oh, babe. I'm so sorry.
I knew she left, but I didn't know why or when.
Yeah.
By the way, I told my mom you're sick and I need to leave the cabin early to take care of you.
She said I could take the bus back, but that there's a storm coming in soon.
So she won't drive me to the bus stop 'til tomorrow morning.
Babe?
You there?
Yeah.
I found the address book.
I found Quentin Finch.
3 minutes later.
Is this Quentin Finch?
Indeed. May I ask who this is?
My name is Ethan Owens.
You gave a diary to my dad, Dick Owens.
I found your number in his address book.
Gotcha. My husband went to college with your father.
He’s the one who told me about his work at the museum.
Does your father need something else from me?
No, but I have a few questions.
I need to know where the diary came from.
Like I told your dad, I found it in a box in the attic.
I need to look through that box.
Why?
Please—I don't have time to explain.
Look, I live in Detroit and I mailed that diary to your dad at an address down in Tennessee.
You’d really come all that way to look through a box of old junk?
I threw most of that crap in the garbage.
What?!
Why?
I need to know what was in the box!
What the hell's going on here?
Shit.
Forget it.
You'd never believe me.
I'm screwed.
Oh, my good Lord.
What?
I've got quite a few boxes in my attic, full of old family mementos.
I come from a long line of hoarders.
That box belonged to Cornelius Finch.
Can you tell me anything about Cornelius?
He was obsessed with the occult.
If you're freaking out about something in that box…
My money’s on witchcraft.
You believe in that stuff?
Well, I don't know about that.
But I don't exactly trust it.
That's why I got rid of Cornelius’s stuff.
What was in the box, Quentin?
I need specifics.
Books about black magic and ancient spells…
Old relics, divination bones, a voodoo doll…
A bunch of worthless trinkets and oddities.
But the diary seemed authentic, like it belonged in a museum or something.
Listen, I found a symbol in that diary and thought it looked cool.
So I got it tattooed on my bicep a few days ago.
I never believed in witchcraft before, but I think the symbol is cursed or something.
I've been having strange symptoms ever since I got inked.
So I need to know more about Cornelius Finch.
Whoa.
A tattoo?!
Holy shit.
What's wrong?!
There was a letter in that box, written by Cornelius.
I still have it somewhere.
My husband kept it for the genealogy scrapbook he's working on.
Nothing but another kind of hoarding, if you ask me.
But God help me, I love him.
The letter could shed some light on your situation.
Let me look for it.
WAIT.
What does it have to do with me?
Hello?
Quentin?!
11 minutes later.
Found it.
It's dated February 19, 1906.
Well, what does it say?!
Cornelius wrote that tattooing was beginning to get popular in New York in the early 1900s.
The first shops and parlors were opened, and Cornelius wanted to get inked.
It looks like he got a geometric occult symbol tattooed on his arm…
And he experienced hallucinations for a few days.
OMG!
He had chronic nosebleeds… and he spoke in tongues, too.
He thought the symbol had been cursed.
What happened to him?!
Well, the letter ends like that.
It simply says that he was cursed.
But I also found an old newspaper clipping in the box…
It reveals the fate of Cornelius Finch.
Shit—what does the newspaper say?
It's Cornelius’s obituary.
It seems he committed suicide.
WHAT?!
How?!
He drowned himself in the Hudson River.
OMG.
I know. The obit was written by his brother.
It doesn't paint Cornelius in a very flattering light.
"Cornelius's obsession with the occult fatally consumed him."
"You cannot drink the cup of the Lord and the cup of demons. 1 Corinthians 10:21."
WHOA.
What?
Is there something else?
Quentin?!
Yeah.
There's something else.
What?
The obit cites Cornelius’s date of death.
Yeah? And?
He committed suicide on February 23, 1906…
Four days after he wrote the letter.
